image.altText: A huge storm over a country town at night.

props.synopsis: Hailstones the size of golf balls battered cars and buildings and ceilings collapsed in a Victorian town as a ferocious storm tore through overnight. It comes amid a forecast of extreme weather for much of Australia's south-east.

title.children: 'All hell broke loose': Huge hail, torrential rain and gale-force winds wreak havoc in Victoria's west

image.altText: A man standing in front of a house

props.synopsis: Investors with 10 or more properties to their name have more debt than smaller-scale investors but use negative gearing and capital gains discounts to keep buying, tax office data shows.

title.children: After years of 'hard slog', Victor has more than 100 rentals — but not everyone agrees the system is fair

image.altText: An aerial shot of the Geelong Waterfront.

props.synopsis: Police are investigating the alleged theft of possibly more than $100,000 from G21 Geelong Region Alliance. The advocacy group is primarily funded by five local councils between Geelong and Colac Otway Shire.

title.children: 'This is ratepayer money': Police probe years-long theft from major advocacy group

image.altText: Judy Small holds a guitar and smiles at the camera

props.synopsis: Judy Small has made her mark in three careers: as a family lawyer, a Federal Court judge, and a singer-songwriter. The 71-year-old is one of 21 people to be inducted into Victorian Honour Roll of Women.

title.children: Celebrated folk performer turned Federal Court judge Judy Small has been added to Victoria's list of 'amazing' women

image.altText: A large grey kangaroo with a white kitchen bin lid stuck around its head.

props.synopsis: Wildlife rescuers in Victoria's Grampians region are reporting multiple cases of kangaroos getting their heads stuck in domestic kitchen bins and say it's because tourists are feeding them.

title.children: Tourists urged not to feed wildlife after spate of bin-diving kangaroo rescues

image.altText: Young Caucasian man taking a self portrait on a couch wearing a brown cap, a black singlet and an orange scarf.

props.synopsis: Jake Bradford has not been seen since his mother reported him missing more than 600 days ago. Police found what they suspect to be human remains during a search of the tiny Victorian town of Dollar.

title.children: Police uncover remains in search for allegedly murdered 21yo Victorian man

image.altText: A firefighter and a man outside a shop.

props.synopsis: The owner of an ebike store which was destroyed in an arson attack wants the government to do more to end the state's tobacco wars. Police believe a gym above the bike shop was the intended target of the attack.

title.children: 'Horrendous': Bike store owner speaks after being caught up in tobacco turf wars

image.altText: A composite image of Leanne Pompeani, with the iamge on the left showing an Asics logo and the logo removed on the right.

props.synopsis: The Melbourne Marathon Festival has apologised after an image of a winning athlete posted to its Instagram page was apparently edited to obscure the logo of a competitor of its naming-rights sponsor.

title.children: Nike-sponsored Melbourne Marathon apologises after sharing photo of winner with Asics logo edited out

image.altText: Bailey Smith screams

props.synopsis: The Western Bulldogs and Geelong agree on a last-minute deal that sends Bailey Smith to the Cats, while Jake Stringer leaves Essendon for GWS as AFL trade period ends with a flurry of late moves.

title.children: Smith moves to Cats, Stringer joins Giants as trade deadline day springs to life in final minutes

image.altText: A man standing in a park with a shirt that says 'I'd rather still be living in Rochy'.

props.synopsis: More than 100 insurance claims are yet to be finalised after flooding damaged 900 homes in Rochester two years ago. Despite this, the community is banding together to support those still in need.

title.children: Every house in this town was damaged by floods two years ago. Hundreds of people are still displaced

image.altText: Elise Hodden looks at the camera with her hand resting on her head during a photo shoot.

props.synopsis: Melbourne man Connor Mathiasson, 23, has been released on bail after being charged over the death of model Elise Hodder. Ms Hodder died on Sunday morning after she was struck by a car in Kooyong.

title.children: Driver granted bail over crash that killed Melbourne model Elise Hodder

image.altText: Toby Greene of the Giants leads his team out onto the SCG for a final

props.synopsis: GWS players face potential AFL sanctions, with an investigation underway after an anonymous complaint about an end-of-season function.

title.children: Giants facing AFL sanction over post-season function

image.altText: A woman is hugging a golden retriever dog

props.synopsis: Deciding when to end the life of an old or sick pet can be incredibly tough, so many animal owners are now seeking help from bereavement counsellors.

title.children: How do you make the heartbreaking decision to say goodbye to a pet?

image.altText: Two young men smile for the camera on the red carpet for the 2019 Logies.

props.synopsis: Radio host, TV star and podcaster Hamish Blake on his secret fitness training, taking up golf, the "barbs that stick in your heart" when raising children, and other parenting challenges.

title.children: 'A fight that's ultimately futile': Hamish Blake on facing his own mortality in his home gym

image.altText: ACT Labor Leader Andrew Barr stands on a stage speaking behind a podium.

props.synopsis: The ACT chief minister says it was a mistake to appoint Walter Sofronoff to head an inquiry into the trial of Bruce Lehrmann.

title.children: Barr says Sofronoff's appointment to board of inquiry a 'mistake'

image.altText: A teenage boy's hands on a table. He is fidgeting, wrapping fingers around his thumb.

props.synopsis: The boy, who was incarcerated in Perth's Banksia Hill Detention Centre and faced 36 criminal charges, has been released from custody without further penalties. A magistrate described him as WA's "most vulnerable child".

title.children: 'State's most vulnerable child': 11yo WA boy released after a total 77 days in custody

image.altText: A group of people holding signs and flags walk in a protest rally.

props.synopsis: Staff at the Australian National University in Canberra have been asked to forgo an agreed pay rise amid efforts to get the university's budget under control.

title.children: 'I know this is a big ask': ANU staff urged to forgo agreed pay rise to keep university afloat

image.altText: a woman giving the finger at a man as he walks away

props.synopsis: Elizabeth Lee made the gesture towards a journalist at a press conference after the ACT Property Council's leaders' debate on Wednesday.

title.children: Canberra Liberals leader Elizabeth Lee makes rude gesture at journalist following tense press conference exchange

image.altText: A local resident and a rescuer stand on debris of a building.

props.synopsis: The Ukrainian president tells politicians his plan contains five main points that rely on Kyiv's allies, including an unconditional invitation to join NATO and specific weapons support.

title.children: Zelenskyy unveils victory plan as Russia reports capture of two Ukrainian villages

image.altText: Five beers are held up as people cheers

props.synopsis: Prague has banned night-time pub crawls organised by travel agencies. Is this the end of the stag do?

title.children: World's thirstiest nation bans organised night-time pub crawls

image.altText: Lisa Marie Presley at the Cartier Flagship Store for a special party to unveil the book "Cartier: Untamed".

props.synopsis: Lisa Marie Presley died before she had the chance to finish her memoir, From Here To The Great Unknown. Per her wishes, her eldest daughter Riley Keough helped it make its way into the world.

title.children: Lisa Marie Presley's posthumous memoir is a sad, shocking and tender look at the price paid for fame

image.altText: Small round balls on a beach

props.synopsis: Hundreds of mysterious black spheres that washed up on three popular beaches in Sydney have been identified as tar balls.

title.children: Mysterious black balls identified after washing up on three Sydney beaches

image.altText: a man stands in a gallery smiling at the camera with art in the background

props.synopsis: Iain Dawson has pleaded guilty to transferring $34,000 of art gallery funds into his own bank account.

title.children: Former art gallery director guilty of theft of $34,000 of Archibald ticket sales

image.altText: A seawall damaged in a storm.

props.synopsis: Roads and beaches on the tropical Cocos (Keeling) Islands in the Indian Ocean remain shut, but a rising tide and further high swells have officials worried that the worst is yet to come.

title.children: 'Absolute freak' swells topple seawalls, bury beaches on Australia's most remote territory

image.altText: Jerry Seinfeld smiling.

props.synopsis: US comedian Jerry Seinfeld walks back a claim he made earlier this year that there is a lack of quality television comedy because "people [are] worrying so much about offending other people".

title.children: US comedian Jerry Seinfeld retracts claim 'extreme left' has ruined TV comedy

image.altText: Gregory Geason on mobile phone outside court.

props.synopsis: A Tasmanian Supreme Court judge is found guilty of one charge each of assault and emotional abuse or intimidation.

title.children: Tasmanian Supreme Court judge found guilty of assault

image.altText: A close up photo of a man wearing a suit and blue tie.

props.synopsis: The US government warns Israel that if it does not improve access to humanitarian aid in Gaza in the next 30 days, American military funding to the country may be cut.

title.children: White House's $26.7b warning to Israel: Improve aid or we'll cut your military funding

image.altText: Ollie Olsen in a 1991 promo shot for his project Third Eye.

props.synopsis: Ian 'Ollie' Olsen, a significant figure in Australia's post-punk scene and a pioneer in experimental electronic music, has died following a lengthy illness.

title.children: Ollie Olsen, celebrated musician and Michael Hutchence collaborator, dies age 66

image.altText: Jess lies on the grass laughing.

props.synopsis: Jess Cerro — aka the singer-songwriter Montaigne — didn't study music in school because the tuition was expensive, but taught themselves guitar and pursued music anyway.

title.children: For years Montaigne assumed their savings were taken care of. Then they realised 'the truth' about their finances

image.altText: A room with ocean views.

props.synopsis: The prime minister's seaside property purchase raised eyebrows, but many politicians have larger property holdings.

title.children: As the PM's 'clifftop' home raises eyebrows, explore the property portfolios of all federal politicians

image.altText: An older woman with short grey hair and rounded glasses smiles.

props.synopsis: The federal government's threat to ban excessive debit card surcharges by 2026 has been welcomed by customers and small businesses who have been hit with higher costs for years — but not everyone is on board.

title.children: 'I was quite shocked': Convenience almost cost one woman $150 in card surcharges

image.altText: A plane with 'Batik' branding begins its take-off from the runway.

props.synopsis: The airline says it will reinstate the Canberra to Denpasar services when market conditions are more conductive.

title.children: Batik Air suspends flights indefinitely between Canberra and Bali four months after they started

image.altText: A family photo of two parents and three young children, against the backdrop of a blue beach.

props.synopsis: Jess Meikle, her husband, their five-year-old twins and four-year-old have embarked on an Australian caravanning extravaganza.

title.children: What's the best age to take your kids on a family gap year?
